@page "/"

<PageTitle>Home</PageTitle>

<h1>Hybrid Authentication Example</h1>

<p>
    This Blazor Web App demonstrates three authentication sources working together
    with a single ASP.NET Core Identity user store (Entity Framework + SQLite):
</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Local accounts</strong> — register &amp; sign in with a username/password stored in the local database.</li>
    <li><strong>LDAP</strong> — authenticate against a corporate LDAP directory. A local account is auto-provisioned on first login.</li>
    <li><strong>Microsoft Entra ID</strong> — sign in via OpenID Connect (SSO). A local account is auto-provisioned on first login.</li>
</ul>

<h3>How it works</h3>

<ol>
    <li>
        <code>AddIdentity&lt;ApplicationUser, IdentityRole&gt;()</code> +
        <code>AddEntityFrameworkStores&lt;ApplicationDbContext&gt;()</code>
        — EF Core owns the Identity stores (users, roles, claims, tokens).
    </li>
    <li>
        <code>AddLdapServices(configuration)</code>
        — registers <code>ILdapService</code> for credential validation <em>without</em> replacing the EF stores.
    </li>
    <li>
        <code>AddOpenIdConnect("EntraId", ...)</code>
        — adds Entra ID as an external OIDC provider. The <code>OnTokenValidated</code> callback
        provisions a local user and signs in via <code>SignInManager</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
        <code>HybridSignInService</code>
        — tries LDAP first, then falls back to local password on the login page.
    </li>
</ol>

